# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1998-commonwealth-games
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The **1930 British Empire Games** were the inaugural edition of what is now known as the Commonwealth Games, and was held in Hamilton, Ontario, from 16 to 23 August 1930.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The event was organized by *Hamilton Spectator* sportswriter Bobby Robinson after he attended the 1928 Summer Olympics in Amsterdam as manager of the Canadian track and field team and was inspired to create a similar event for the British Empire.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] After campaigning for the idea among contacts he met at the Olympics, he was asked to organise the first British Empire Games in Hamilton.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] Fellow Hamilton journalist Ivan Miller helped with the organizing committee.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The sports included athletics, boxing, lawn bowls, rowing, swimming, and wrestling.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The opening ceremony and athletics events were held at Civic Stadium (later renamed Ivor Wynne Stadium) in east Hamilton.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The event was opened by the Governor General of Canada, Lord Willingdon, on 16 August.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] Canadian triple jumper Gordon Smallacombe claimed the debut gold medal a few hours later.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The 1930 British Empire Games made use of pedestals for dignitaries to present medals to winning athletes, as proposed by Bobby Robinson.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] This inspired the Olympic medal podium ceremonies which began at the 1932 Winter Olympics.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The **1934 British Empire Games** were the second edition of what is now known as the Commonwealth Games, held in England, from 4–11 August 1934.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The host city was London, with the main venues at Wembley Park and the White City Stadium, although the track cycling events were in Manchester.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Seventeen national teams took part, including the Irish Free State (the only Games in which they participated, although an all-Ireland team competed at the 1930 Games).
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The 1934 Games had been originally awarded to Johannesburg, South Africa, but the change of venue to London was made due to concerns regarding the treatment of black and Asian athletes by South African officials and fans.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Six sports were featured in the Games with rowing being dropped from 1930 but cycling making its first appearance.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Athletics took place at the White City Stadium, while boxing, wrestling, and aquatics (swimming and diving) were held at the Wembley Empire Pool, where the swimming pool would be converted overnight into an arena with 7,000 additional seats brought in to increase the capacity to 12,000.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Lawn bowls was held at two clubs in Paddington and Temple, while the cycling was held at the Fallowfield Stadium in Manchester.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Events for women athletes included a debut in athletics; the previous games had women's events in swimming and diving only.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The Wembley Empire Pool was built specifically for the games on the instruction of Arthur Elvin and had been completed in just nine months, opening 10 days before the start of the Games on 25 July.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] (Teams participating for the first time in **bold**).
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] The **1938 British Empire Games** were the third British Empire Games, the event that evolved to become the Commonwealth Games.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Held in Sydney, Australia, from 5–12 February 1938, they were timed to coincide with Sydney's sesqui-centenary (150 years since the foundation of British settlement in Australia).
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Venues included the Sydney Cricket Ground (the main stadium), the North Sydney Olympic Pool and Henson Park.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] An estimated 40,000 people attended the opening ceremony.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] A men's residential village was established within the grounds of the Sydney Showground, while the female athletes were housed in hotels.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] The star of the games was the Australian athlete Decima Norman, who won five gold medals in track and field.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Margaret Dovey, later married to Australian prime minister Gough Whitlam, finished sixth in the 220 yards breaststroke.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Due to the onset of World War II, the games were not held again until 1950.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The **1950 British Empire Games** were the fourth staging of what is now called the Commonwealth Games.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] It was held in Auckland, New Zealand, between 4 and 11 February 1950, after a 12-year gap from the third edition of the games due to World War II.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The fourth games were originally awarded to Montreal, Canada and were to be held in 1942 but were cancelled due to the War.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The Games were declared open by Sir Bernard Freyberg.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The opening ceremony was held at Eden Park and was sold out with 40,000 people attending.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] Eden Park also served as the main venue, while the closing ceremonies were held at Western Springs Stadium.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] Other venues included the Auckland Town Hall and the Newmarket Olympic Pool.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] A 1950 British Empire Games documentary film of the games was made by the New Zealand National Film Unit.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] At the 1950 British Empire Games all the teams won at least one medal.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The **1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games** were held in Vancouver, British Columbia, from 30 July to 7 August 1954.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] This was the fifth edition of the event that would eventually become known as the Commonwealth Games, the second post-war Games, the second Canadian Games after the inaugural event in Hamilton and the first event since the name change from British Empire Games took effect in 1952.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Other bids to stage the Games were received from Toronto, Montreal and Hamilton.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The main venue was the Empire Stadium, which had been specifically constructed for the games at the cost of £500,000.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Work on the 25,000 seated stadium started in October 1953 and the keys were handed over to Stan Smith (General chairman of the games) on 12 July 1954.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The games were attended by 24 nations and 662 competitors.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was the first time that the games gained a television audience, when CBC and NBC transmitted pictures to an estimated 100 million North American viewers.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Recordings of the games were also shown on the BBC Television Service, beginning a consistent association between the BBC and the Commonwealth Games which only ended in 2026.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was at these games that the "Miracle Mile" took place between Roger Bannister and John Landy at the Empire Stadium.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] This was the first time these two (and at that time the only two) sub-four-minute mile runners appeared in the same race, and also the first time two runners broke four minutes in the same race.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] On the same afternoon, Jim Peters, the holder of the world best time for the marathon, entered the stadium 17 minutes ahead of his nearest rival, but collapsed on his final lap, and never completed the race.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 24 teams were represented at the 1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The **1958 British Empire and Commonwealth Games** (Welsh: *Gemau Ymerodraeth Prydain a'r Gymanwlad* 1958) were held in Cardiff, Wales, from 18 to 26 July 1958.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was the sixth edition of what would come to be known as the Commonwealth Games, the second Games held in the United Kingdom, and the second held under the name **British Empire and Commonwealth Games**.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Thirty-five nations sent a total of 1,130 athletes and 228 officials to the Cardiff Games and 23 countries and dependencies won medals, including, for the first time, Singapore, Ghana, Kenya and the Isle of Man.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 178,000 tickets were eventually sold during the Games.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The Cardiff Games introduced the Queen's Baton Relay, which has been conducted as a prelude to every Commonwealth Games ever since.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The British Empire and Commonwealth Games, including the opening and closing ceremonies, were held at the Cardiff Arms Park.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The following venues were used during the Games.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 36 countries and territories were represented (and 1,100 athletes), being the largest number to date, with a significant number of teams competing for the first time at the 1958 British Empire and Commonwealth Games.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] At Cardiff Arms Park, an anti-apartheid crowd protested at the all-white South African team; games organisers responded that non-white South Africans were ineligible as their associations were not affiliated to the international federations.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] South Africa left the Commonwealth in 1961 and next appeared at the Games in 1994.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The **1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games** were held in Perth, Western Australia, from 22 November to 1 December 1962.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Athletic events were held at Perry Lakes Stadium in the suburb of Floreat and swimming events at Beatty Park in North Perth.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was held after the 1962 Commonwealth Paraplegic Games for wheelchair athletes.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Most venues other than the specifically constructed Lake Monger Velodrome, Beatty Park, and Perry Lakes Stadium, were existing facilities.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 35 teams were represented at the 1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] (Teams competing for the first time are shown in **bold**).
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Note: The medals used at these Games were the first to have a neck chain.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] All previous games had their medals in presentation boxes.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] The **1998 Commonwealth Games** (Malay: *Sukan Komanwel 1998*), officially known as the **XVI Commonwealth Games** (Malay: *Sukan Komanwel ke-16*), were a multi-sport event held in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] The 1998 Games were the first to be held in Asia, and the last Commonwealth Games of the 20th century.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] For the first time ever, the Games included team sports.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] Around 3,638 athletes from 70 Commonwealth member nations participated at the Games, which featured 214 events in 15 sports with 34 of them collected medals.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] Kuala Lumpur was selected to stage the games at the General Assembly of the Commonwealth Games Federation in Barcelona, Spain during the 1992 Summer Olympics.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] The athletes' village (Vista Kommanwel) with a capacity of 6,000 people is located beside the National Sports Complex in Bukit Jalil.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] It consists of three tower blocks of 30 storeys and six hillside blocks of 19 storeys with 1,300 condominiums and an International Shopping Zone.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] The International Broadcast Centre was constructed at Angkasapuri, Kuala Lumpur, while Mint Hotel (now Nouvelle Hotel) served as the Main Press Centre. stage broadcaster Radio Televisyen Malaysia was the host broadcaster of the event.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] The 16th Commonwealth Games opening ceremony took place on 11 September 1998 at 20:00 MST (UTC+08:00).
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] During the ceremony, approximately 4,840 Soka Gakkai Malaysia volunteers displayed coloured flip cards which depicted sporting images, flags of the Commonwealth nations and messages that heralded the first games in Asia in the 68 years since their inception.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] The ceremony began with the arrival of dignitaries including the Chairman of Commonwealth Games Federation Michael Fennel, Prince Edward, Sultan of Brunei Hassanal Bolkiah, Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad, the Yang Dipertuan Agong and Malaysian minister of Youth and Sports Muhyiddin Yassin.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] Then came a performance about a Malaysian rainforest by 2,000 school children who dressed as birds, bees and flowers.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] After the performance, the Queen's message was delivered in the ceremonial baton, which had begun the final stages of its journey on the back of an elephant.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] 1978 Commonwealth Games badminton gold medal winner Sylvia Ng took the last lap with the baton and handed it off to Koh Eng Tong, a weightlifter who won a gold medal in weightlifting for Malaya in the 1950 British Empire Games, to take the final few feet to Prince Edward.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] Contrary to tradition, the games were officially opened by the Malaysian head of stage, Yang di Pertuan Agong Tuanku Jaafar by striking the gong three times.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] A burst of fireworks and blurring of the giant bunga raya and a 16-gun salute which represents 1998 Commonwealth Games being the 16th-edition games, signified the beginning of the games.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] The Commonwealth Games flag was then brought into the stadium raised to the theme song of the Games *Forever As One* written by local composer, Goh Boon Hoe.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] Malaysian bowler Shalin Zulkifli later take the oath on behalf of the athletes.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] The ceremony concluded with a 40-minute performance, titled "Aur di Tebing" (Bamboo at the riverside) with the theme 'Unity towards Progress', which was conveyed through dance, music, and intricate human graphics.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] 2,000 performers swirled and danced carrying trays of *bunga emas* (golden flowers) on their heads during a mass silat display.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] The show told the Malaysian history from ancient Malacca to the present development in Malaysia, its political, economical and technological achievements as well as its people's vision of peace, prosperity and unity and lifestyle.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] The closing ceremony took place on 21 September 1998 at 20:00 MST (UTC+08:00).
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] The ceremony began with Queen Elizabeth and King Ja'afar's arrival in a limousine, for inspection of guards of honour of the Royal Malay Regiment.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] The British national anthem *God Save The Queen* was played followed by Malaysia's national anthem *Negaraku*.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] This was followed by a 3-part cultural performance led by a band performance by 400 school students from Johor, Negeri Sembilan, Selangor and Kuala Lumpur followed by an upbeat song performance from local artist Jay Jay.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] A contemporary farewell dance performance by local artists, featured Siti Nurhaliza and Noraniza Idris concludes the cultural performance.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] Soon afterwards, all the participants, flag-bearers and the volunteers march into the main ground of the stadium and Olympic council of Malaysia president Tan Sri Hamzah Abu Samah later declared the returning of the flags of all the participating nations.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] Then the protocol was resumed and the 69 Commonwealth Games Associations flagbearers positioned themselves in a rostrum and the Commonwealth Games flag was lowered by the Malaysian armed forces.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] Fennel handed the flag to the Chief Citizen of Manchester city, Gordon Conquest.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] Following, the official speeches were delivered and Queen Elisabeth was invited to declare the Games closed.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] In a new protocol step, the Queen has withdrawn from the stadium alongside the King of Malaysia and other authorities, after the guard of honour march song has played, followed by Auld Lang Syne.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] The Prime Minister of Malaysia, Mahathir Mohamad, later made an announcement to declare 28 September 1998 as a national public holiday to commemorate the nation's success in hosting the games.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] The ceremony concluded with a concert performed by Six Commonwealth Top Singers representing the six regions of the Commonwealth Federation and local artists.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] 69 Commonwealth Games Associations appeared at the 1998 Games.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] Cameroon, Kiribati, Mozambique and Tuvalu made their Commonwealth Games debut.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] The only absent country was Nigeria, which was suspended from the Commonwealth of Nations due to the tyrannical dictatorship of Sani Abacha who had died earlier that year.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] The host nation achieved its best-ever haul of ten gold medals, which has since been surpassed by its achievement in the 2010 Commonwealth Games, where Malaysia won twelve gold medals.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] This is an edition marked by several unprecedented facts in the history of the Commonwealth Games.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] Not only because it was the first to be held in Asia and the first that was not opened by a member of the host nation's royal family.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] And, taking advantage of these factors, the Commonwealth Games Federation decided in 1994 that from this edition onwards, team sports could enter the Games program.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] As a result, the number of sports included rose from 10 to 16.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] The case studies determined that three team sports were eligible: field hockey (men and women), netball (women) and rugby 7's (men).
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] Adding to aquatics (swimming) (athletics), boxing, badminton, cycling (road), weightlifting, and lawn bowls as compulsory sports.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] Another spot was reserved for squash, which was an evaluation sport and was in contention to become mandatory in the next edition.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] There was still a spot for a local sport, and the organizers chose ten-pin bowling, which was included as an extra sport because of its popularity in the country and also because of the presence of a newly constructed venue that could host the sport.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] However, there was some controversy surrounding the removal of wrestling that had been present in all previous editions because of its low popularity in Malaysia.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] In front of 20,000 fans at the Petaling Jaya Stadium, rugby sevens in particular were an enormous success, with New Zealand collecting its 100th Commonwealth Games medal with a 21–12 win over reigning world champions Fiji.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] The man of the match was the Jonah Lomu, who had worked tirelessly during the last 10-minutes of the final.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] Led by veteran star David Campese, Australia took the bronze, beating Samoa 33–12.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] In the squash event, many had anticipated a close match between Michelle Martin and Sarah Fitz-Gerald, who had both comfortably won their respective semi-finals.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] Fitz-Gerald had won the previous two years' World Championships and Martin the three prior to that, and so it was with some surprise to many that Martin took the gold in three straight sets 9–0, 9–6, 9–5.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] Fitz-Gerald did avenge this defeat in the final of the world championship later that year, in what many people regard as the greatest women's final ever, coming back from 8–2 down in the fifth to retain her title.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] Martin also teamed up with Craig Rowland to take the Commonwealth mixed doubles gold.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] Erika-Leigh Stirton took five of the six available gold medals in the rhythmic gymnastics only being beaten into second place in the team event in the hosts took gold.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] Only the top ten successful nations are displayed here.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] The ranking in this table is consistent with International Olympic Committee convention in its published medal tables.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] By default, the table is ordered by the number of gold medals the athletes from a nation have won (in this context, a "nation" is an entity represented by a Commonwealth Games Association).
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] The number of silver medals is taken into consideration next and then the number of bronze medals.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] If nations are still tied, equal ranking is given and they are listed alphabetically by their three-letter country code.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] The logo of the 1998 Commonwealth Games is an image of the national flower of Malaysia, the hibiscus (the *bunga raya*), the first games logo to introduce the colour yellow.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] (All previous logos had been red, white and blue to reflect the colours of the British Union Flag.) The red, blue, white and yellow colours represents the colours of the Malaysian national flag and Malaysia as a confident, young, dynamic nation.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] The yellow pollens represent the six regions of the world that includes the 68 Commonwealth member nations.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] The official mascot of the 1998 Commonwealth Games is an orangutan named *Wira* (Malay for "warrior" or "hero").
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] It is said that the orangutan is the largest and probably the most intelligent primate in Asia which lives in the tropical rainforests of Malaysia.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] The adoption of orangutan as a games' mascot is to represent the friendly personality of Malaysia as the games' host as well as the charm, intelligence, and sporting ability of the participating athletes.
[src:1998-commonwealth-games/1998-commonwealth-games] A total of 55 companies and organisations sponsored the games, including Malaysian state-owned enterprises.
